"""
mkt-original commentary — Leviticus 22–23 (77 verses)
Ch22: Priestly qualifications, acceptable offerings, blemish-free requirement
Ch23: The festival calendar (moadim) — Sabbath, Passover, Firstfruits, Weeks,
      Trumpets, Yom Kippur, Sukkot
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

LEVITICUS_ORIGINAL = {
  "22": {
    "1": "<p>Chapter 22 continues the regulations for the priestly office, shifting from personal qualifications (ch. 21) to ritual qualifications for eating sacred food and presenting acceptable sacrifices. The chapter operates at two levels: (1) the priestly household's access to the holy portions (<em>qodashim</em>), and (2) the physical integrity of animals brought as offerings. Both sections share the same principle: holiness demands wholeness, and what is given to YHWH must be the best, not the defective or disqualified.</p>",
    "2": "<p><strong>yinnazru</strong> (Niphal imperfect of <em>nazar</em>, 'to separate, consecrate, dedicate'): 'Aaron and his sons shall keep away from the holy things of the people of Israel.' The root <em>nzr</em> gives us both <em>nazir</em> (Nazirite, one who separates himself by vow) and <em>nezer</em> (the high priest's diadem/crown). The same root covers both voluntary consecration and required separation. Here the Niphal (reflexive passive) means the priests must separate themselves — in context, this means while ritually impure they must abstain from the holy offerings. Holiness and impurity are mutually exclusive poles; the priest cannot stand in both simultaneously.</p>",
    "3": "<p><strong>nitmetah</strong> (Niphal of <em>tame</em>): ritual defilement cuts a priest off from the holy food. The text says such a priest will be 'cut off' (<em>nikhretah</em>) from YHWH's presence — the same <em>karet</em> language used for the gravest covenant violations. This reflects the seriousness of holiness-boundary violations even within the priestly system: the remedy is purification and waiting, but there is no shortcut. The priest who eats holy food while impure is not merely ritually irregular — he has treated the holy as common (<em>chillel</em>).</p>",
    "4": "<p>The list of disqualifying impurities — <em>tzara'at</em> (skin disease), genital discharge (<em>zob</em>), contact with a corpse-contaminated person, semen emission — mirrors the purity laws of chapters 13-15. The common thread is that all these conditions involve either death (corpse, skin disease), reproductive disruption, or bodily emission — all associated with mortality and the body's boundaries. Holiness is associated with life, wholeness, and integrity; these conditions mark the opposite. The solution is time, washing, and waiting for evening — the body's natural restoration cycle.</p>",
    "8": "<p><strong>nevela</strong> (carcass of an animal that died naturally) and <strong>trefah</strong> (an animal torn by wild beasts) — these two categories are prohibited food for priests, though they could be given to the resident alien or sold to a foreigner (Deut 14:21; contrast with Lev 22:8 prohibiting the priest from eating them). The issue is not the food category in the abstract but the priest's heightened holiness standard. <em>Trefah</em> later becomes the broad term in rabbinic halakha for any non-kosher meat; here it has its original specific meaning of an animal mauled by predators. The priest must not eat what was not killed in the prescribed sacrificial manner.</p>",
    "9": "<p><strong>chet</strong> (sin/penalty) and <strong>metu bo</strong> (they will die because of it): the phrase 'they shall therefore keep my charge' (<em>shamru et mishmarti</em>) employs the standard custodial language of priestly responsibility. The doubling of the root in 'keep my charge' (<em>mishmeret</em> = 'what is to be kept/guarded') emphasizes the active, ongoing nature of priestly duty. Death as the penalty for mishandling holy things appears also in Numbers 4:15-20 (Kohathites), reinforcing that the Levitical system treated holiness violations as capital matters.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The category of those permitted to eat the <em>terumah</em> (priestly portion) is carefully defined: <em>zar</em> (outsider, non-priest), <em>toshav</em> (resident/tenant of the priest), and <em>sakhir</em> (hired laborer) are excluded. The contrast with permitted persons (v.11-13) shows the rule is about covenant status and household belonging, not ethnicity: a slave purchased by a priest or one born into his household — bound to the priestly household — may eat. The priestly household is a closed economy of holiness; membership matters more than origin.</p>",
    "14": "<p><strong>be-shegagah</strong> (inadvertently, by mistake) — if a layman eats the holy food by accident, he must restore it at full value (<em>chamishito yosif alav</em>, 'he shall add a fifth to it'). The 20% surcharge appears also in guilt offering law (Lev 5:16) and restitution law (Lev 6:5). The principle: even unintentional violations of the holy have real consequences requiring real remedy. Grace does not mean consequences are erased; it means a path of restoration is provided. The fifth part (<em>chamishit</em>) signals that trespass against the holy incurs more than simple restitution — there is a premium for having encroached.</p>",
    "18": "<p><strong>tamim</strong> (perfect, without blemish, whole): the term used throughout the offering laws for the required quality of sacrificial animals. Its root <em>tmm</em> means 'to be complete, perfect, whole' — the same root gives <em>tom</em> (integrity, wholeness, blamelessness) used of Job's character (Job 1:1) and the psalmist's walk (Ps 15:2). Applied to animals, <em>tamim</em> means without physical defect. Hebrews 9:14 applies the concept directly to Christ: he offered himself 'without blemish' (<em>amōmon</em>, the LXX translation of <em>tamim</em>) to God. The animal regulation of Lev 22:18-25 is the type that explains why Christ's offering could be effective where animal offerings could not.</p>",
    "20": "<p><strong>lo leratzon yihyeh lachem</strong> (it will not be acceptable/pleasing for you): the passive sense of <em>ratzon</em> (pleasure, acceptance, favor) as the criterion for a valid offering. <em>Ratzon</em> comes from the root meaning 'to be pleased with, to accept favorably.' The acceptance of an offering by YHWH is not automatic — it depends on the integrity of what is offered and the integrity of the offerer. Isaiah 1:11-15 shows YHWH rejecting Israel's abundant offerings because the offerers' hands were bloodied — acceptability is not merely a ritual category but a relational one.</p>",
    "21": "<p><strong>shelem</strong> (peace/fellowship offering): the term is from the root <em>shalom</em> (peace, wholeness, completeness). The peace offering is the only sacrifice where the offerer, the priests, and YHWH all receive portions — it is inherently communal. The three subtypes (todah/thanksgiving, neder/vow, nedavah/freewill) appear in ch. 7. The <em>tamim</em> requirement applies here too: <strong>lo yihyeh bo mum</strong> (there shall be no defect in it). The completeness of the peace offering's animal mirrors the shalom it embodies — communion with a holy God requires wholeness in what is brought.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The catalog of disqualifying blemishes: blind (<em>iveret</em>), injured (<em>shavurah</em>), maimed (<em>charutz</em>), running sore (<em>yabbelet</em>), scab (<em>garav</em>), scurvy (<em>yallefet</em>). The specificity of the list is important: it is not a general principle but an enumeration, preventing priestly discretion in accepting substandard animals. The purity of the offering system depends on clear, public, verifiable standards. The same principle appears in mal. 1:8 where Malachi condemns the priests of his era for accepting blemished animals — the law was meant to prevent precisely this corruption.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Prohibition on offering animals with crushed, torn, or cut testicles. The emasculation of animals was common in surrounding cultures for various purposes. The prohibition here may relate to the wholeness-requirement: the animal must be complete, not altered. In the Holiness Code's logic, cutting or crushing represents a deviation from created wholeness. Note that Deut 23:1 extends similar logic to human membership in the assembly: the eunuch is excluded from the assembly (though Isa 56:3-5 reverses this exclusion for eunuchs who keep the Sabbath and hold fast the covenant).</p>",
    "25": "<p><strong>min ben nechar</strong> (from the hand of a foreigner): even sacrifices brought by resident aliens or non-Israelites must meet the <em>tamim</em> standard. This confirms that the blemish laws are not merely about Israelite social purity but about what is intrinsically acceptable to YHWH. The offering standard transcends the identity of the offerer. This aligns with the trajectory toward universal worship: Isaiah 56:7 envisions foreigners whose burnt offerings and sacrifices are accepted on YHWH's altar.</p>",
    "27": "<p>A newborn animal must remain seven days with its mother before it is eligible for offering. The seven-day waiting period mirrors the circumcision-timing (Lev 12:3) and possibly the completion-of-a-week principle that runs through the creation narrative. The prohibition on killing the mother and her young on the same day (v.28) has parallels in Deut 22:6-7 (the bird's nest law) — a concern for the natural order and against gratuitous destruction of reproductive capacity, reflecting the creation stewardship mandate.</p>",
    "28": "<p><strong>oto ve-et beno lo tishchatu beyom echad</strong> (it and its young you shall not slaughter on the same day): the prohibition on killing parent and offspring the same day. This is one of several Levitical laws that recognize animal family bonds — not by anthropomorphizing animals but by maintaining a certain reverence for the natural order that YHWH created. Maimonides (Guide 3:48) explained it as prevention of cruelty; modern readers see it as ecological wisdom. The underlying logic is consistent with the Holiness Code's concern that Israel not act with callous disregard for creation.</p>",
    "29": "<p><strong>toda</strong> (thanksgiving offering): a subtype of the peace offering in which the motivation is gratitude for a specific act of divine deliverance. The same-day eating rule (v.30) applies: <em>leratzonkhem tizbachu</em> — the urgency of consuming it reflects the immediacy and specificity of the thanksgiving. Psalm 107 is the great thanksgiving liturgy envisioning four types of delivered people bringing their <em>toda</em>; Ps 50:14 calls the <em>toda</em> the true sacrifice YHWH desires. The <em>toda</em> is the offering of relationship and response, not transaction.</p>",
    "30": "<p><strong>mimacharat lo yinotir</strong> (you shall not leave any of it until morning): the time-constraint on the todah offering creates urgency that distinguishes it from the two-day peace offering. The perishability-limit on holy food prevents its commercialization: you cannot stockpile thanksgiving. The pattern also appears in the manna (Exod 16:19-20) — YHWH's provision is meant to be received and consumed in trust, not hoarded. Each day's grace is sufficient for that day.</p>",
    "31": "<p><strong>ushemar'tem mitzvotai va-asitem otam</strong> (You shall keep my commandments and do them): the transition to the Holiness Code's ethical summary. The dual verb — keep (<em>shamar</em>) and do (<em>asah</em>) — is the standard covenant obedience formula: internalize and then act. <strong>Ani YHWH</strong> (I am YHWH) grounds the command in divine identity, not merely divine authority.</p>",
    "32": "<p><strong>velo techallelu et shem qodshi veniqdashti betoch benei Yisrael</strong>: 'You shall not profane my holy name, but I will be hallowed among the people of Israel.' <em>Chillul hashem</em> (profaning the Name) and <em>kiddush hashem</em> (sanctifying/hallowing the Name) are the two poles of this verse — the most concentrated statement in the Torah of the concept that YHWH's reputation among the nations is at stake in Israel's behavior. The Niphal of <em>qadash</em> — 'I will be hallowed/sanctified' — is passive: YHWH's holiness is revealed through Israel's obedience. Ezekiel extensively develops this theme (Ezek 36:20-23): Israel's exile profaned YHWH's name among the nations; the restoration will vindicate it.</p>",
    "33": "<p><strong>ani YHWH mekadishchem hamotzi etchem me-eretz Mitzrayim</strong>: 'I am YHWH who sanctifies you, who brought you out of the land of Egypt.' The closing formula links sanctification to the Exodus: YHWH's holiness-making activity in Israel is inseparable from his historical redemption of Israel. Israel was not first made holy and then redeemed — redemption came first (Exod 12-14), then the covenant and its holiness demands (Exod 19-Lev). The logic is grace → law, not law → grace.</p>"
  },
  "23": {
    "1": "<p>Chapter 23 is the Torah's primary festival calendar, presenting the annual cycle of <em>moadim</em> (appointed times/meetings). It organizes Israel's time theologically: the year is structured around YHWH's appointments with his people. The chapter is not merely a religious calendar but a theology of time — every week (Sabbath), every spring (Passover, Firstfruits, Weeks), every fall (Trumpets, Yom Kippur, Sukkot) is claimed as YHWH's territory. The NT reads the festival calendar typologically: Christ is the Passover lamb (1 Cor 5:7), the firstfruits of the dead (1 Cor 15:23), and the Spirit is poured out at Pentecost/Shavuot (Acts 2).</p>",
    "2": "<p><strong>moadei YHWH</strong> (appointed times of YHWH): the plural <em>moadim</em> from the root <em>y'd</em> (to appoint, meet at an appointed time). <em>Moed</em> is the word for 'tent of meeting' (<em>ohel moed</em>) — the tabernacle is itself a <em>moed</em>, a place and time of divine appointment. By calling the festivals <em>moadei YHWH</em>, the text frames them not as Israel's religious observances but as YHWH's invitations: he sets the times, he calls the assembly. <strong>mikra qodesh</strong> (holy convocation/sacred proclamation): <em>mikra</em> from <em>qara</em> (to call, proclaim) — these assemblies are called assemblies, summoned by divine invitation. The festivals are not merely human celebrations but responses to divine summons.</p>",
    "3": "<p><strong>shabbat shabbaton</strong> (sabbath of rest): the intensive doubled form (<em>shabbaton</em> adds the nominal suffix for emphasis) distinguishes the weekly Sabbath as the foundational <em>moed</em>. The Sabbath heads the list because all the festivals are built on the Sabbath-principle: sacred rest is the paradigm that the annual festivals replicate and elaborate. <strong>mikra qodesh</strong> recurs — the Sabbath is not merely a rest day but an assembly day, a day of sacred gathering. <strong>kol melacha lo taasu</strong> (you shall do no work) — the negative form of Sabbath observance; the positive form is the <em>mikra qodesh</em>.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The transition phrase <em>eleh moadei YHWH</em> (these are the appointed feasts of YHWH) marks the beginning of the annual festival calendar proper, distinguishing the recurring weekly Sabbath (v.3) from the annual appointments. The phrase <em>asher tiqreu otam bemoadam</em> (which you shall proclaim at their appointed time) confirms that proclamation is essential: the festivals do not simply arrive, they are announced. The priestly calendar function included proclaiming (literally calling out, <em>qara</em>) the new moon and festival dates — a calendrical authority that later became significant in rabbinic disputes.</p>",
    "5": "<p><strong>Pesach laYHWH</strong> (Passover of/for YHWH): the 14th of the first month (<em>Nisan/Abib</em>) at twilight (<em>bein ha-arbayim</em>, literally 'between the two evenings'). The Passover lamb was killed at twilight and consumed during the night that followed — the night of the 14th becoming the 15th (Jewish day begins at nightfall). Paul's identification of Christ as 'our Passover lamb who has been sacrificed' (1 Cor 5:7) and John's chronology of the crucifixion on the eve of Passover (John 18:28; 19:14) both operate within this precise calendrical framework.</p>",
    "6": "<p><strong>Chag haMatzot</strong> (Festival of Unleavened Bread): the seven-day feast beginning on the 15th, immediately following Passover. <em>Matzot</em> (unleavened bread) commemorates the hasty exodus (Exod 12:33-34, 39 — no time for the dough to rise). Paul reads the leaven allegorically: 'Cleanse out the old leaven that you may be a new lump, as you really are unleavened. For Christ, our Passover lamb, has been sacrificed. Let us therefore celebrate the festival, not with the old leaven, the leaven of malice and evil, but with the unleavened bread of sincerity and truth' (1 Cor 5:7-8). The seven-day feast creates a week of consecration following the Passover.</p>",
    "7": "<p><strong>melechet avodah</strong> (laborious work, heavy labor): the compound phrase distinguishes forbidden work on festival days from permitted work. <em>Melacha</em> alone (as in the Sabbath command, Exod 20:9-10) means any ordinary work; <em>melechet avodah</em> specifies burdensome/servile labor. This distinction allowed the preparation of food on festival days (Exod 12:16) — not every activity was suspended, only the servile labor associated with ordinary workdays. The rabbis developed this distinction extensively in tractate Yom Tov.</p>",
    "10": "<p><strong>reishit qetzirchem</strong> (the first of your harvest): the wave-sheaf offering of the firstfruits of the barley harvest — the first grain to ripen in the spring. <em>Reishit</em> (first, beginning) carries the same root as <em>Bereshit</em> (In the beginning, Gen 1:1) and connects to the firstfruits theology running through the Torah: the first of everything belongs to YHWH and is given as the pledge that secures the whole harvest. <strong>omer</strong> (a sheaf or a unit of dry measure): the specific term for the wave-sheaf of barley. 1 Cor 15:23 applies the firstfruits type to the resurrection: 'Christ the firstfruits, then at his coming those who belong to Christ.'</p>",
    "11": "<p><strong>mimocharat hashabbat</strong> (on the day after the Sabbath): the contested phrase that determines when to begin counting the 50 days to Pentecost (Shavuot). Two interpretations dominated in the Second Temple period: (1) the Pharisaic/rabbinic: 'Sabbath' = the Passover high-day Sabbath (the 15th of Nisan), so the count starts on the 16th; (2) the Sadducean/Karaite: 'Sabbath' = the weekly Sabbath within the Passover week, so the count always starts on Sunday, making Shavuot always fall on Sunday. The dispute is still unresolved. If interpretation (2) is correct, the Resurrection (first Sunday after Passover), the Wave Sheaf offering, and Pentecost all fall on Sundays by design — the day after the Sabbath becomes the day of new creation.</p>",
    "13": "<p><strong>minchah chadasha laYHWH</strong> (a new grain offering to YHWH): the wave-sheaf offering includes both the sheaf and a grain offering (<em>minchah</em>) plus a whole burnt offering of a lamb. The grain offering at firstfruits is described as 'new' (<em>chadasha</em>) — it marks the opening of the new harvest year before YHWH. Until this offering is made, the new grain cannot be eaten (v.14). The logic: the first gives permission for the rest. In giving the first to YHWH, the whole harvest is consecrated as given by him.</p>",
    "14": "<p><strong>ad etzem hayom hazeh</strong> (until this very day): the restriction on eating grain from the new harvest until the wave-sheaf offering is made applies universally ('wherever you dwell') — it is not limited to the tabernacle/temple context but is a national calendar discipline. The phrase 'until this very day' marks a permanent statute (<em>chuqqat olam</em>). The theological logic: first acknowledge YHWH as the giver before receiving the gift. The firstfruits offering is an act of faith that what has been given can be given back without loss.</p>",
    "15": "<p><strong>usefartem lachem</strong> (you shall count for yourselves): the counting of the Omer — 49 days from the wave-sheaf to Shavuot. The Omer counting is unique in the Torah in that the counting itself is the commandment, not merely the endpoint. The act of counting each day creates anticipation and intentionality; the 49-day journey from Passover (redemption from Egypt) to Shavuot (giving of the Torah at Sinai, in rabbinic tradition) structures the spiritual journey from liberation to covenant. The <em>Sefirat HaOmer</em> (counting of the Omer) became one of the most prominent Jewish daily practices.</p>",
    "16": "<p><strong>chamishim yom</strong> (fifty days): the number that gives Pentecost its Greek name (<em>pentekostos</em>, fiftieth). The Greek word passed directly into Christian use for the festival of the Spirit's outpouring (Acts 2). The fifty-day structure connects to the Jubilee (50-year cycle) and suggests a pattern of completion-plus-one: seven times seven = 49 (completion), plus the 50th = the day that transcends the cycle. Shavuot/Pentecost is the day after completion — the day of the new gift that follows the full cycle.</p>",
    "17": "<p><strong>lechem tenufah shetayim</strong> (two loaves as a wave offering): the two leavened (<em>chametz</em>) loaves waved at Shavuot are unique — virtually every other grain offering at the altar was unleavened (Lev 2:11). The use of leavened bread may symbolize Israel as it actually is (not idealized) — brought before YHWH with its mixture of good and bad, its fermentation, its imperfection. Some see the two loaves as representing Israel and the Gentiles who would be incorporated at Pentecost/Acts 2 (the reversal of Babel, with people from every nation understanding). The loaves are baked, not merely raw grain — processed, mature harvest brought as an offering.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The gleaning laws (Lev 19:9-10 repeated) appear in the middle of the Shavuot regulations — an interruption that is actually an integration: the harvest festival must include care for the poor and the stranger. The festival of thanksgiving for YHWH's provision is incomplete without sharing that provision with the vulnerable. The Book of Ruth enacts this law: Boaz's harvest fields at Shavuot-time become the site where Ruth (a Moabite stranger) gleans and is redeemed. Ruth is traditionally read at Shavuot.</p>",
    "24": "<p><strong>zikhron teruah</strong> (a memorial of blowing/alarm): the Feast of Trumpets on the first of the seventh month. <em>Teruah</em> is the loud, broken blast of the shofar (or silver trumpets) — associated with alarm, battle-cry, and proclamation. The term <em>zikhron</em> (memorial, remembrance) raises the question: what is being remembered? The text does not specify; the content of the memorial is left implicit. In rabbinic tradition, Rosh HaShanah (the New Year, which later became the name for this day) is the day of divine remembrance — YHWH remembers his people and inscribes their fate for the year. The shofar blast calls both Israel to attention and YHWH to remembrance.</p>",
    "25": "<p><strong>mikra qodesh</strong> (holy convocation) and <strong>lo taashu melechet avodah</strong> (you shall not do servile work): the same formula as other festival days. The seventh month (Tishri) contains the most concentrated cluster of holy days: Trumpets (1st), Yom Kippur (10th), Sukkot (15th-21st), and Shemini Atzeret (22nd). The seventh month's density of festivals corresponds to the seventh day's Sabbath — the seventh is the consecrated, climactic unit in the Creator's calendar.</p>",
    "27": "<p><strong>Yom HaKippurim</strong> (Day of Atonements, plural): the plural form (<em>kippurim</em>) may intensify the singular or refer to the multiple atonement acts of the day (for the high priest, for the sanctuary, for the people). The word <em>kippur</em> here is a noun from the verb <em>kipper</em> (to make atonement/to expiate) — Yom Kippur is literally the 'day of the kipper-act.' <strong>ve-initem et nafshoteichem</strong> (you shall afflict your souls): <em>innui nefesh</em> (soul-affliction) is the physical observance of Yom Kippur — fasting being its principal expression. <em>Nefesh</em> here refers to the whole person through the physical appetite: afflicting the body-self is the Yom Kippur discipline.</p>",
    "28": "<p><strong>ki yom kippurim hu lekapper aleichem</strong> (for it is a Day of Atonement to make atonement for you): the <em>kipper</em> (Piel, make atonement) verb here takes Israel as its object (<em>aleichem</em>). This verse is the only occurrence in Leviticus 23 that uses the atonement language in connection with Yom Kippur — the festival calendar references the sacrifice theology of chapter 16. The prohibition on work (<em>kol melacha</em>) and the fast together constitute the full observance: both abstinence and affliction on the day when the high priest's blood-work atones for the whole covenant community.</p>",
    "29": "<p><strong>karet</strong> penalty for not observing the Yom Kippur fast: 'Every person who is not afflicted in that very day shall be cut off from his people.' <em>Karet</em> (cutting off) is the covenant excision penalty — removal from the community either through death or exclusion. Its application here to the Yom Kippur fast shows that atonement was not merely a priestly ritual done on Israel's behalf without Israel's participation — the people were obligated to participate through the fast. The atonement required active reception, not passive observation.</p>",
    "30": "<p><strong>vehibadeti et hanefesh hahi</strong> (I will destroy that soul/person): in addition to the <em>karet</em> penalty from the community, YHWH himself will 'cut off' the non-observant — divine excision reinforces covenant excision. The doubled sanction (cut off from the people, AND destroyed by YHWH) intensifies the gravity of Yom Kippur. This is one of only a few places where both forms of the <em>karet</em> penalty are stated together. The day is not to be taken lightly.</p>",
    "32": "<p><strong>shabbat shabbaton hu lachem</strong>: the intensive <em>shabbat shabbaton</em> (used also of the weekly Sabbath in v.3 and the Sabbatical year in Lev 25:4) is applied to Yom Kippur — marking it as the Sabbath of Sabbaths among the festival calendar, the supreme rest-day. The fast from sunset to sunset on the 10th of Tishri makes it the only twenty-five-hour Sabbath in the calendar. <strong>ve-initem et nafshoteichem</strong> repeated: the soul-affliction command bookends the Yom Kippur section (vv.27, 32) for emphasis.</p>",
    "33": "<p>The Sukkot/Booths festival section (vv.33-44) is the longest in chapter 23, reflecting its importance as the climactic harvest festival. Sukkot runs seven days (15th-21st of Tishri) plus an eighth day solemn assembly (<em>atzeret</em>, v.36). It combines agricultural thanksgiving (end of the harvest year) with historical memorial (the wilderness sojourn). The abundance of Sukkot — freewill offerings, communal celebration, the four species — contrasts with Yom Kippur's austerity five days earlier. Together they form a theological dyad: atonement then celebration, affliction then joy.</p>",
    "34": "<p><strong>Chag haSukkot</strong> (Festival of Booths/Tabernacles): <em>sukkot</em> (booths, temporary shelters) are the defining feature — Israelites dwell in them for seven days to remember the wilderness journey (v.43). The word <em>sukkah</em> appears in various non-festival contexts to mean a temporary shelter or the divine canopy over Israel (Isa 4:6; Amos 9:11 — 'I will raise up the <em>sukkah</em> of David'). The Johannine prologue's 'the Word became flesh and dwelt (<em>eskēnōsen</em>, tabernacled) among us' (John 1:14) may deliberately echo Sukkot language — the Incarnation as the ultimate <em>sukkah</em>.</p>",
    "36": "<p><strong>atzeret</strong> (solemn assembly, closing assembly): the eighth day of Sukkot — not technically part of the seven-day Sukkot festival but a concluding 'gathering' day. The root <em>atzar</em> (to restrain, hold back, close) suggests the <em>atzeret</em> is the day that closes the festival season — the final day before returning to ordinary time. John 7:37-38 sets Jesus's proclamation of living water on 'the last day, the great day of the feast' — likely the <em>Hoshana Rabbah</em> (seventh day of Sukkot) or the <em>Shemini Atzeret</em> (eighth day), when water-libation ceremonies were performed in Second Temple practice.</p>",
    "37": "<p><strong>eleh moadei YHWH</strong>: the summary formula restates the calendar's structure. The variety of offerings required at each festival (<em>olah, minchah, zevach, nesakhim</em> — burnt offering, grain offering, sacrifice, and drink offering) shows that the full range of Israel's offering vocabulary was engaged throughout the year. No single offering type alone served the full relational range; the calendar pressed all of them into use at their appropriate times.</p>",
    "40": "<p><strong>peri etz hadar</strong> (fruit of a splendid/beautiful tree, traditionally the <em>etrog</em>/citron), <strong>kaparot temarim</strong> (branches of palm trees, <em>lulav</em>), <strong>anaf etz avot</strong> (boughs of leafy/thick trees, traditionally myrtle), and <strong>arvei nachal</strong> (willows of the brook): the four species carried during Sukkot. <em>Hadar</em> (splendid, glorious) appears elsewhere of YHWH's majesty (Ps 104:1) and of human dignity (Lev 19:32 'honor the face of the old man'). The binding of the four species into the <em>lulav</em> bundle for waving became one of the most distinctive Jewish festival rituals. Nehemiah 8:15 describes Ezra's restoration of Sukkot including gathering these specific branches.</p>",
    "41": "<p><strong>chuqqat olam leDoroteichem</strong> (a perpetual statute for your generations): the permanent, trans-generational character of the Sukkot ordinance. The <em>chok</em> (statute) distinguishes laws whose reasons are not stated from <em>mishpatim</em> (judgments/laws) whose rationale is implied by justice. Sukkot is given as a <em>chok</em> — its observance is commanded before its rationale is given (which comes in vv.42-43). Obedience precedes explanation; trust in the lawgiver precedes understanding of the law.</p>",
    "42": "<p><strong>bashsukkot teshvu shivat yamim</strong> (you shall dwell in booths seven days): the dwelling (<em>yashav</em>) is to be actual habitation, not merely decoration. The seven-day duration mirrors the creation week. <strong>kol ha-ezrach beYisrael</strong> (all who are native Israelites): the commandment is universal within Israel — not just the wealthy who can build elaborately or the priests, but everyone. The leveling democratic character of Sukkot: for seven days all Israelites live in identical temporary shelters, recalling their ancestors' common precariousness in the wilderness.</p>",
    "43": "<p><strong>lema'an yeda'u doroteichem ki basukkot hoshavti et-benei Yisrael behotzi'i otam me-eretz Mitzrayim</strong>: 'so that your generations may know that I made the people of Israel dwell in booths when I brought them out of the land of Egypt.' The <em>lema'an yeda'u</em> (so that they may know) pattern is the knowledge-of-YHWH formula: ritual acts are designed to produce generational knowledge of YHWH's identity and saving acts. The wilderness booths were not a choice but a condition — temporary, exposed, dependent on YHWH for provision. Annual booth-dwelling re-enacts that dependence, preventing amnesia of the original neediness from which YHWH redeemed Israel.</p>",
    "44": "<p><strong>vayedabber Moshe et moadei YHWH el-benei Yisrael</strong>: 'Thus Moses declared to the people of Israel the appointed feasts of YHWH.' The closing formula for the festival calendar confirms that Moses is the mediator who communicates YHWH's appointed times to Israel. The <em>moadei YHWH</em> (YHWH's appointments) bookend the chapter — the festivals are YHWH's, not Israel's invention. Israel's role is reception, proclamation, and observance; the calendar is given, not constructed.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-original', 'leviticus')
    merge_comm(existing, LEVITICUS_ORIGINAL)
    save_comm('mkt-original', 'leviticus', existing)
    for ch in ['22', '23']:
        vv = existing.get(ch, {})
        print(f'  ch{ch}: {len(vv)} verse(s) with original commentary')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
